What is R ?

is a programming language mainly used for statistical computing, data analysis and graphics. it is a free, open source language developed as a GNU project and so licensed under the General Public Licence (GPL).

Downloading and Installing R and RStudio

can be downloaded from the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN). It is available for multiplatform operating systems (Linux, Windows and Mac OS).

can be downloaded and installed for free for a personal use from the RStudio web page. RStudio is a Graphical User Interface (GUI) as well as an environment for R simplifying its use for statistical programming and data analysis in a user-friendly way.

R Interfaces

The simple R version is composed of a window console (see the part 1 in the graphic below) where the R code is written and then executed by just typing <Enter> or <Ctrl+Enter> (in Windows system) and <Cmd+Enter> (in Mac Os). The output is displayed in the same window (see window 1 in the graph below), if the task performed is the display of statistics, and in a new window (see part 2, graph below) if the output is a graphic, the help or a list of objects.

To save the history of the executed code that can be re-used in the further sessions, the entire work can be written in a script. The latter is saved with the extension .R and executed into the R console using the command source(ScriptName.R) or in a terminal, using the command Rscript followed by the ScriptName.R

RStudio is a GUI that allows simplicity and interactivity by adding many helpful functionality to the use of R. Four windows form the Rstudio interface. The first one is dedicated to writing the R code script (1). The second, is a console (2) where results of the executed code are displayed. It is equivalent to that of the R simple interface without a GUI. The console is usually used to execute temporary code that dont need to be saved for further use. RStudio interface contains also a window that shows the imported data files or data created by the user (3) and lastly, a window displaying the contents of the current working directory, the generated plots, and other useful information (4).

R environment

The R environment is made up of native packages that contain many functions each of them running a special task.

The R Base Package

The R Base is the basic version that we obtain when installing R for the first time. We can obtain the list of the default installed packages with the R Base Package on the CRAN site.

To get the number of the installed packages, we use the nrow() function:

options(repos="https://cran.rstudio.com")
nrow(installed.packages())
## [1] 362

R Packages extension

When dealing with more advanced statistical analysis or econometric modeling, the R base packages may not be sufficient to handle all the required models by the user. In this case, we can use the external packages developed by the large R Developers Community. A package can be installed using the command install.packages(PackageName) and then loaded in memory using library(PackageName).

The number of packages offered by CRAN is continuously increasing. The list of the current packages available can be viewed at the CRAN.

Likewise, we can use the nrow() R command to calculate their number:

nrow(available.packages())
## [1] 18618

We can also check on the CRAN site the available packages by topic to focus on those we are interested in, such as Econometrics, Finance, Time Series, Graphics, etc.

R Packages for Datascience

The tidyverse is a set of packages used to deal with datascience issues in R as same as Pandas and Scikit-Learn libraries for Python language. It has been written initially by Hadley Wickham, a statistician, software developer and professor of statistics, currently Chief Scientist at RStudio. The tidyverse packages work as a unified framework because they share common data representations. This package-parent is designed to make it easy to install and load multiple tidyverse packages in a single step. The installation of tidyverse allows the use of eight packages:

dplyr, tidyr, tibble, forcats, readr, purrr, stringr and ggplot2 to achieve different tasks related to data analysis, graphics and statistical modeling (see the figure below).

  1. dplyr: Offers a grammar of data manipulation. It is a fast, consistent tool for working with data frame like objects, both in memory and out of memory.

  2. tidyr: Is a tool for creating data as dataframe format and tools for working with missing values.

  3. tibble: Provides tools for formatting data more than the traditional data frame.

  4. forcats: Contains tools for working with categorical variables (Factors).

  5. readr: Provides a fast and friendly way to read rectangular data.

  6. purrr: Is a complete and consistent functional programming toolkit for R.

  7. stringr: Is a simple and consistent wrappers for common string operations.

  8. ggplot2: Offers very powerful tools for creating elegant data visualizations using the grammar of graphics.

To check the content of tidyverse package we first install and load it in memory.

R files system

The R script is written in a simple text document and saved with .R extension, while R database files are saved with .RData extension.

Getting help on a R function

To get help on a specific R function we can use both the following commands:

help ( FunctionName )

? FunctionName.

For instance, to get help on the mean function, we can type:

help(mean)
## starting httpd help server ... done

Or

? mean

The help gives a description of the function, its usage, list a few main references and offers some practical examples for its use.

Creating, modifying and deleting data

First of all, R can be used as a simple calculator:

2*2
## [1] 4
100/5
## [1] 20
2^10
## [1] 1024

We can then store the result of a calculation using the famous R assignement symbol <- in an object which can be used later.

a <- 2^10

And then we can apply on the object any function such as log (x), abs (x), sqrt (x), etc.

log(a)
## [1] 6.931472

We can create data from scratch, either by combining variables created separately as R objects or in one step. The structure of the created objects may have different types in R. An object may be, character, numeric (real or decimal), integer, logical or complex.

To begin, we create some variables from online real data on covid19, available on the internet on Worldometers web site.

# Creating variables.

countries <- c("France", "Germany", "Spain", "Italy")
CovidCases <- c(1502763, 580415, 1331756, 759829)
CovidDeaths <- c(38289,10904,36495,39412)

In the case we do not explicitly indicate the variable nature, R recognises it anyway by attributing the right type. In the example above, the variable (object) countries is assigned by R as a character type, because it is put within brackets. As the other two variables contain numbers, they are thus recognised as numeric.

To combine the three variables in one single database, we can use the dataframe structure. In short, a dataframe corresponds to a sheet structured as rows and columns, where each column is a variable, each row is an observation, and each cell contains a single value. The first row contains usually the columns name.

By assigning covidata as a name to the data resulting from the combination of countries, CovidCases and CovidDeaths objects, we get a new dataset structured as a dataframe format using the function data.frame ().

# Creating 'covidata' set as a data frame.

covidata <- data.frame(countries,CovidCases,CovidDeaths)

Covidata is now the new dataset containing the three objects (Countries, CovidCases, CovidDeaths) structured like a sheet by rows and columns.

To save a copy of it in the current directory, we can use the save () function.

# Saving a copyt of 'covidata' in the local working directory.

save(covidata,file="covidata.RData")

As described in the help, the saved objects can be read back from the file at a later date by using the function load () or attach (or data in some cases).

To delete data files or directories definitely, we use unlink (DataName) function as follows:

# Deleting the "covidata" file from the local directory.

unlink("covidata.RData")

We notice that at this stage, notwithstanding we have deleted the saved file, the data opened in memory (covidata) still exists and so, we can continue to use it in the current session. Data in memory can be removed using the rm (DataName) function or by choosing not to save the file, when closing the R programs (session).

To check the type of covidata file, we can use the class (DataName) command:

# Checking the class category of 'covidata'.

class(covidata)
## [1] "data.frame"

To show its structure, we use the str (DataName) function:

# Looking at the structure of 'covidata'.

str(covidata)
## 'data.frame':    4 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ countries  : chr  "France" "Germany" "Spain" "Italy"
##  $ CovidCases : num  1502763 580415 1331756 759829
##  $ CovidDeaths: num  38289 10904 36495 39412

To visualize the whole dataset, we can just type its name in the console:

# Showing the 'covidata' content.

covidata

This way of doing things is not convenient when the database is very large containing many rows and columns. In this case, it is recommended to just check the beginning and the end of the file, using either functions:

head (DataName)

or

tail (DataName).

To visualise data in an external sheet, we can use the View (DataName) command (with V in capital letters):

# Visualising data in a sheet. 

View (covidata)

To show all names of data columns, we can use the names() function.

# Showing the names of all the columns (variables) of "covidata" that is three in this case.

names(covidata)
## [1] "countries"   "CovidCases"  "CovidDeaths"

Importing external data files

R has some functions in the Base package allowing to read external data, mainly, Comma Separated Values (CSV) and Delimited data file (delim). Many functions from other packages can read files in different format such as Excel, SAS, SPSS, Stata, etc. These functions are more suited for advanced use of R. We focus in this tutorial on how to read CSV and Excel files.

Reading (importing) CSV data files

Comma-separated values are data in text format where each value is separated by a comma. Separation or delimitation may be a tabulation or any other delimiter such as a semicolon, etc.

The following R function

\(\text{read.table(file="DataName", header=TRUE, sep=" ", dec=" ", quote= "\"")}\)

can be used to read almost all data formatted as text files and creates as an output a data frame from it.

# Read the "crimes_SC.csv" dataset where every single data is separated by a Semicolon.

crimes1<- read.table(file="crimes_SC.csv", sep=";", header=TRUE, dec=".")
# Read the "crimes_C.csv" dataset where data is separated by a Comma.

crimes2<- read.table(file="crimes_C.csv", sep=",", header=TRUE, dec=".")
# Read the "crimes_SC.csv" dataset where data is separated by a Tabulation.

crimes3<- read.table(file="crimes_T.csv", sep="\t", header=TRUE, dec=".", quote = "\"")

Reading Excel data files

To read Excel files, we can use one of the many functions available in the tidyverse package cited above. Before reading \(xls\) or \(xlsx\) data, we should first load the readxl library.

library("readxl")

To look at the content and usage of readxl package.

 help(package="readxl")

Reading crimes.xls data file in R using the function read_xls contained in readxl package and assign the output in crimes_xls file.

crimes_xls <- read_xls("crimes.xls", sheet=("data"))

Merging datasets

Merging data sets is a part of data preparation (cleaning) which allows to have a single database for the entire study. The need for merging new data with the existing one may appear during the study process because new questions arise as the study progresses, or that the data collection operation itself takes place in different steps.

The merging of data can be performed in two different ways. Adding new variables (columns) or adding new individuals (rows). The first type is an horizontal merge where new data are joined or combined with the current one. The second type is a vertical stacking where new data are overlaid to increase the rows number. Obviously, a third possibility may exist where a merging operation adds new rows as well as new columns to the existing data.

There are several functions present in the package dplyr that perfom the joining of data in a very easy way. To get an idea on how these functions work, we can imagine two data sets data1 and data2 and then combining them in different ways using dplyr tools.

# Creating the first dataset "data1" as a tibble format.

# This first data file (data1) contains three variables: Animals, their babies, and their nature as wild or domestic.

data1 <-tibble(Animals=c("Cat","Chicken","Dog","Elephant","Giraffe","Gnu","Lion",
                         "Panda","Penguin","Rabbit"),
Baby=c("Kitten","Chick","Puppy","Calf","Calf","Calf","Cub","Cub","Chick","Kitten"),
Nature=c("Domestic","Domestic","Domestic","Wild","Wild","Domestic","Wild","Wild",
         "Wild","Domestic"))
# Creating the second data file "data2" as a tibble format.

# The second data file (data2) contains also three variables: Animals, their babies, and a new variable, on the 'weight of babies' at birth measured in a kilogram. We notice that the variable 'Animals' includes now two new animals: 'Turkey' and 'Duck'. Likewise, for their babies and weight at birth. 

data2<- tibble(Animals=c("Cat","Chicken","Dog","Elephant","Giraffe","Gnu",
                         "Lion","Panda","Penguin","Rabbit","Turkey","Duck"),
Baby=c("Kitten","Chick","Puppy","Calf","Calf","Calf","Cub","Cub","Chick",
       "Kitten","Poult","Duckling"), 
Weight=c(0.08,0.9,0.45,90,99,36,8,0.1,0.32,0.03,0.05,0.05))

I. Data joining

When joining data we can distinct between two types, joins that combine data and those that filter the data.

One of the main issues when joining different data files is the specification of one or more common keys on which basis the merging will be done. R can implicitly recognise the key(s) used to merge data by comparing and choosing common columns in the different files as a merge criterion. The option, by=(merging_keys) can be used in case where a specific key is chosen instead.

1. Combining joins

Four type of joins can be identifid from the dplyr package: left_join, right_join, inner_join and full_join

left_join

The left_join is the most used operation for data sets combining. This method gives the priority to the data file placed on the left (data1 in the following code). The output contains all the individuals present in file data1 and add to it new information from the file data2 for individuals whose identification keys are common. The symbols name given to files according to their position are, \(x\) for the left side file and \(y\) for the right side one.

data_left<- left_join(data1, data2)
## Joining, by = c("Animals", "Baby")

right_join

The right_join does the inverse operation compared to the previous one. The reference file in merge is the one placed on the right (data2).

data_right<- right_join(data1, data2)
## Joining, by = c("Animals", "Baby")

inner_join

The inner_join operation keeps all the information (columns) for only the common individuals between merging files. It is suited for instance in the case when the requested output is a balanced data between different input files.

data_inner <- inner_join(data1, data2)
## Joining, by = c("Animals", "Baby")

full_join

The full_join method as its name suggests produces as output a data file that contains all the data from the different files used in the merge. Rows that are not common, based on key merge, will have their columns marked NA (for not available).

data_full <- full_join(data1, data2)
## Joining, by = c("Animals", "Baby")

2. Filtering joins

There are two functions that can be used to merge data while filtering based on the merging key.

semi_join

The semi_join function selects the observations from data2 (\(y\)) that are present in data1 (\(x\)), without adding new columns from \(y\)s file. In other words, this operation keeps at the end, only the observations of \(x\) table that are also present in \(y\) table.

data_semi <- semi_join(data1,data2)
## Joining, by = c("Animals", "Baby")

anti_join

The anti_join does the opposite of semi_join. It keeps only observations of \(x\) file that are absent from \(y\). In the case where all observations from \(x\) are present in the \(y\) file, the output turns to be a zero observation as in the case below.

data_anti <- anti_join(data1,data2)
## Joining, by = c("Animals", "Baby")

II. Data stacking

Sometimes we need to put together different data files by pooling them in a vertical way, rather than joining them horizontally. One of the well known examples to illustrate this case is the panel data format.

The bind_row() function from dplyr package can be used to combine files by vertical pooling. The output of bind_rows() will contain a column if that column appears in any of files used as inputs. It is very important to notice here that the name of variables (columns) must be the same in all data sets used as inputs. Any variable with a different name will be considered as a new variable in the output.

# The following code read three Excel files (f2010.xls, f2012.xls and f2014.xls) and assign them to three data frames: f2010, f2012 and f2014.

library("readxl")
f2010 <- read_xls("f2010.xls")
f2012 <- read_xls("f2012.xls")
f2014 <- read_xls("f2014.xls")

Before pooling the data, it is interesting to explore each file entering in data stacking. We limit ourselves in this example to the first file, but we can run the same code for the rest of files.

Computing basic statistics

The general purpose behind descriptive statistics is the exploration of data by computing different measures to know their central tendency, dispersion and distribution, and the links that may exist between variables, before going further in the data analysis and statistical modeling.

When analyzing data, it may be interesting to distinguish between, on the one hand, quantitative and qualitative variables and between univariate and multivariate data analysis, on the other hand. Depending on the nature of variables, several tools can be used to analyse, visualize and model the data.

In the rest of the work, the crimes database provided with this tutorial will be used to illustrate the different R functions dedicated to statistical analysis.

First, we read the crimes data file from excel format (\(xls\)) using read_xls function.

# Loading "readxl" library in memory.

library("readxl")
# Reading "crimes.xls" file using "read_xls" function.

crimes <- read_xls("crimes.xls", sheet="data", col_names=TRUE)

We can see from the output above that crimes data has 95 observations and 9 variables. The variables department name and region name are typed as character. The type numeric is attributed to the rest of the quantitative variables.

It is important to know the type of variables before performing any kind of analysis, as the tools and methods that can be applied to them depending on their nature.

To explore quantitative variables we can use native functions in R one at a time such as min, max, mean, sd, median, etc.

# Computing the Minimum of poverty_index.

min(crimes$poverty_index, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 15.7118

It is interesting to notice here that the selection of the variable poverty_index from the data frame crimes is marked by a dollar symbol ($). We could imagine using just a comma instead. If we try to do so, R will generate an error. So, the general rule for subsetting variables from a database, is the use of a dollar symbol after the name of the data file. Then, the selected variable to be analysed is put after the dollar symbol.

By adding the option na.rm=TRUE when computing statistics, we tell R to remove non-available data (na) before doing the computation. In the present case, there are no missing values in poverty_index, it does not matter using or not this option. However, this option should be used if the analyzed variable contains missing values.

# Computing the Maximum of poverty_index.

max(crimes$poverty_index, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 24.0673
# Computing the Mean of poverty_index.

mean(crimes$poverty_index, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 18.94455
# Computing the Sdandard Deviation of poverty_index.

Univariate plot

To visualise graphically a single variable, we can draw a simple univariate plot using plot() function built in R base.

The basic information needed to get a simple plot is the name of variable. More options can be then added to improve the plot. For the above graphic showing poverty index for instance, we can add the following options:

main: is used to give a general title to the graph.

xlab: is used to give a title to \(x\) axis. It should be noted that the \(x\) axis title in an univariate plot is just the index order of observations in the sample. In the present case, as departments are sorted by their code (from 1 for Ain to 95 for Val-dOise) they appear with this order on the \(x\) axis, and so their position on the plot is given according to the same order.

ylab: is used to give a title to \(y\) axis.

type: This option is used to choose the graph type (\(p\) for points. Other types: l for lines, o for both point and lines. For more details you can refer to the help using, help(plot.default).

pch: is used to choose a plotting symbols such as solid lines, filled circle, filled square, etc. See help(pch) for a complete list.

cex: is a numerical vector giving the amount by which plotting characters and symbols should be scaled relative to the given default.

col: is used to give color name or code of the type of plotting.

Bivariate analysis of quantitative data

When checking for the link between two variables, we can either draw a scatter plot or compute the correlation coefficient to evaluate quantitatively that link.

Plotting relationship between variables

To draw the scatter plot between crimes and poverty, we can use the same plot () function seen above.

# Scatter plot between "crimes" and "poverty_index"

plot(x=crimes$poverty_index, y=crimes$crimes, 
     main="Relashioship between Crimes and Poverty", xlab="Poverty Index", 
     ylab="Crimes", type="p", pch=20, cex=1, col="blue")

From the scatter plot between crimes and poverty, we can observe a positive link in the sense that for regions or departments with low levels of poverty correspond also to low level of crimes. The contrary is true, but with more dispersion than for the lower levels of crimes and poverty.

Computing the correlation coefficient

We can test association between two quantitative variables, using the cor() function. It allows the use of the three traditional methods to compute the correlation coefficient: Pearsons product moment correlation coefficient, Kendalls \(tau\) or Spearmans \(rho\).

# Computing the correlation coefficient between "crimes" and "poverty_index' using the Pearson method. 

cor(crimes$crimes, crimes$poverty_index, method="pearson")
## [1] 0.4988923

The obtained coefficient of 0.50 is positive confirming the link shown in the scatter plot. But at this step, we just observe the correlation level. We can not make conclusions about it. In order to do so we should run a test on statistical significance. As the link is supposed to be linear the t-Student type test can be chosen in this case.

The function in R that computes the correlation coefficient while running the statistical significance test is cor.test().

# Performing the statistical significance test of the correlation between "crimes" and "poverty_index" using "pearson" method.

cor.test(crimes$crimes, crimes$poverty_index, alternative="two.sided",
         method="pearson", conf.level=0.95)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  crimes$crimes and crimes$poverty_index
## t = 5.5513, df = 93, p-value = 2.666e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.3305895 0.6364422
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.4988923
# Performing the test for statistical significance of the correlation between "crimes" and "poverty_index" using "spearman" method, which is a non-parametric one. This method is suited when the supposed link between variables is not linear.

cor.test(crimes$crimes, crimes$poverty_index, alternative="two.sided", 
         method="spearman", conf.level=0.95)

##       rho

The tested null hypothesis \(H_{0}\) is defined as follow: true correlation equals to zero. The Student-test output shows a \(p-value\) equals to zero allowing to reject the \(H_{0}\) hypothesis in favour of the alternative one \(H_{1}\) (true correlation is not equal to 0) and then concluding that the observed link between crimes and poverty is statistically significant.

Bivariate analysis of qualitative data

To test the association between two categorical variables we interact them in a cross table. This cross-tabulation can be used to derive three probability laws: joint probability, marginal probability and conditional probability that are the base of elaborating and estimating more advanced probability models.

Cross tabulating also allows to test the independence between two categorical variables using the Chi-square \(\chi\) test.

Cross-tabulation

To perform the interaction between two categorical variables, we create from crimes and poverty_index two new versions based on the mean of each of them, as the threshold of division into 0 and 1 categories. Thus, the new categorical variable is a dummy variable equals to one if the value of the original quantitative variable is greater than its mean and 0 otherwise.

For the interpretation of the dummy variable of crimes, for instance, level one indicates that the corresponding department belongs to the high crime category and level zero indicates the contrary.

To create dummies we use the ifelse() function that allows to test a conditional statement (\(ifelse (condition, yes, no)\)) and returns two responses: \(yes\) if the condition is TRUE and \(no\) if it is FALSE.

# Creating a dummy for "crimes", named 'crim_degree' based on the mean threshold of "crimes".

crimes$crim_degree <- ifelse(crimes$crimes>mean(crimes$crimes), 1,0 )

# Creating a dummy for "poverty_index", named 'poverty_cat' based on the mean threshold of "poverty_index".

crimes$poverty_cat <- ifelse(crimes$poverty_index>mean(crimes$poverty_index),1,0)

There are many ways to get a cross-taulation in R. We choose in this application to use the CrossTable() function because its implementation is similar to S-Plus crosstabs() and SAS Proc Freq (or SPSS format). Moreover, it performs Chi-square, Fisher and McNemar tests of the independence of all table factors. To get more information on this function see the help using ? CrossTable().

# Performing cross-tabulation between "crim_degree" and "poverty_cat" using "CrossTable()" function.

# Insalling the package "gmodels" to get "CrossTable()" function.

Estimating the linear model (regression) parameters

Linear modelling is a framework to model causality link between two variables, the output variable, \(y\), and the input variable \(x\) when the presupposed relationship linking them is linear. In economics, \(y\) is called the explained, dependent, or endogenous variable, while the \(x\) is named, explanatory, independent or exogenous variable(s).

The regression technique may be used in practice to achieve one of these three main objectives:

  1. Analysing the relationship between two or more variables.

  2. Predicting the value of the explained variable (\(y\)) as a function of a given level of the explanatory variable(s) (\(x\)).

  3. Determining the effect (impact) of \(x\) on \(y\).

When dealing with linear modelling, we distinguish between the mathematical model \(y= f(x)\) where \(f(x)\) is a function of \(x\) and a statistical model that allows to estimate the link between \(x\) and \(y\).

By supposing linearity of the \(x\) function in \(x\), we obtain the following deterministic statistical model:

\[\begin{equation} \tag{1} f(x)= \alpha + \beta x \end{equation}\]

The stochastic linear regression equation is obtained by the addition of a random \(error\) term supposed to capture any omitted (unobserved) factor from the model specification.

The random regression equation can be written as follow:

\[\begin{equation} \tag{2} y = \alpha + \beta x + \epsilon \end{equation}\]

Where,

\(y\): is the endogenous (explained) variable.

\(x\): is the exogenous variable or a vector if there is more than one variable.

\(\alpha\) and \(\beta\): are the unknown coefficients to be estimated from the data using estimation techniques such as, Ordinary Least Squares (OLS), Generalized Methods of Moments (GMM) or Maximum Likelihood estimator (ML).

\(\epsilon\): is the error term supposed to be independent and identically distributed (\(i.i.d.\))

The term that appears most important when we estimate the parameters of the equation (2), is the error term (\(\epsilon\)). Indeed, as the error term captures all factors omitted from the model, the main objective is to find, as far as possible, a specification which makes it possible to minimize this term.

In order for the linear regression model to be properly applied, it must meet a number of criteria. Without being exhaustive, a reliable estimate must respect the following constraints:

  1. Linearity link between the response (\(y\)) and the predictor(s) (\(x\)).

  2. Independence of error terms (absence of auto-correlation).

  3. Homoscedasticity of errors (Constant variance of error terms).

  4. Independence of predictors (Absence of collinearity).

  5. Absence of outliers or high-leverage points.

Among the above constraints on the use of the linear framework, the first, third, and forth must be checked every time it is a question of estimating the coefficients of the linear model. Otherwise, the estimates we obtain may be biased. In the application that follows we will assess each of these issues and introduce the R functions that deal with each of them.

OLS estimation of the linear regression model

Different alternatives may be used to estimate linear model parameters. The OLS method is the most frequently used method in the empirical studies to estimate the linear regression model coefficients.

From equation 2, we can write:

\[\begin{equation} \tag{3} \epsilon_{i}=y_{i}-\alpha - \beta x_{i} \end{equation}\]

The main objective of each estimation is to minimise the \(\epsilon_{i}\) term. We may choose between two possibilities:

  1. \(min \sum|u_{i}|\)
  2. \(min \sum(\epsilon{i})^{2}\)

Following the second proposition, we put \(S=\sum(\epsilon{i})^{2}\)

\[\begin{equation} \tag{4} = \sum(y_{i}-\alpha-\beta x_{i})^2 \end{equation}\]

Let \(\widehat{\alpha}\) and \(\widehat{\beta}\) two estimators for \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\), respectively. To obtain \(\widehat{\alpha}\) and \(\widehat{\beta}\), we derive from the equation 4 with respect to \(\alpha\) and then to \(\beta\).

The derivative with respect to \(\alpha\) is:

\[\begin{equation} \tag{5} \frac{\partial S}{\partial \alpha}=-2\sum(y_{i} - \alpha - \beta x_{i}) \end{equation}\]

The derivative with respect to \(\beta\) is:

\[\begin{equation} \tag{6} \frac{\partial S}{\partial \beta}=-2\sum x_{i}(y_{i} - \alpha - \beta x_{i}) \end{equation}\]

By putting equations 5 and 6 equal to zero we obtain the two following normal equations:

\[\begin{equation} \tag{7} -2\sum(y_{i} - \alpha - \beta x_{i})= 0 \end{equation}\]

\[\begin{equation} \tag{8} -2\sum x_{i}(y_{i} - \alpha - \beta x_{i})= 0 \end{equation}\]

By solving algebraically the equation (7) we get the estimator \(\widehat{\alpha}\) of \(\alpha\) as follows:

\[\begin{equation} \tag{9} \widehat{\alpha}= \bar{y} - \widehat{\beta} \bar{x} \end{equation}\]

By replacing the value of \(\widehat{\alpha}\) got from (9) into the equation (8) and solving, we obtain the estimator \(\widehat{\beta}\) of \(\beta\):

\[\begin{equation} \tag{10} \widehat{\beta}= \frac{\sum({x_{i}-\bar{x}}) (y_{i}-\bar{y})}{\sum({x_{i}-\bar{x}})^{2}} \end{equation}\]

By replacing the two estimators \(\widehat{\alpha}\) and \(\widehat{\beta}\) into the equation 3, we obtain the estimated errors value (residuals) as follow:

\[\begin{equation} \tag{11} \widehat{\epsilon{i}}=y_{i} - \widehat{\alpha} - \widehat{\beta} x_{i} \end{equation}\]

Since \(\;\;\widehat{y}= \widehat{\alpha} + \widehat{\beta} x_{i}\), we can also write \(\;\;\widehat{\epsilon{i}}=y_{i}-\widehat{y}\)

Application. The determinants of crime

In this application the objective is to estimate the determinants of crime using French data in 2011 on crimes. The variable crimes that we consider as the dependent variable, include also all committed incidents and offences by department. It is obtained from Direction Centrale de la Police Judiciaire (DCPJ). The rest of variables is collected from the site of the French National Institute of Statistics and Economic Studies (INSEE). To get information about the variables definition, you could also refer to the sheet named variables in the provided Excel file.

The available variables in the crimes.xls file are:

  • dep_code: French departments code (from 1,,95).

  • dep_name: Departments name.

  • region_name: Regions name.

  • gdp_2011: Gross domestic product in 2011 by department.

  • crimes: Total number of committed crimes, incidents, and offences in 2011 by department.

  • poverty_index: Poverty ratio, given by department.

  • population: Total number of population by department.

  • unemp_rate: Unemployment rate by department.

  • big_region: Large regions, is a variable computed by summing the existing
    French regions, to have six large geographic areas. So, every big region contains a different number of departments.

Main question

In this study case, suppose that we have done first a literature review on the determinants of crime and we have found some explanations to the criminal behaviour. We then have chosen to focus on the socio-economic determinants. The objective is to try to explain criminal behaviour due to socio-economic factors. Moreover, we aim at assessing if there exists a heterogeneity between regions in terms of criminality.

The empirical equation to be estimated can be written as follows:

\[\begin{equation} \tag{12} crimes_{i}= \alpha + \beta_{1} gdp_{i} + \beta_{2} poverty_{i} + \beta_{3} unemp_{i} + \beta_{4} population_{i} + \epsilon_{i} \end{equation}\]

Model improvement: variables scaling

Following the assessment of model fit criteria and the information obtained from descriptive statistics, one way to improve the current OLS estimates is to rescale variables while keeping the link between them unchanged. A logarithmic transformation may reduce the heterogeneity in the relationship linking the poverty index to crimes. Furthermore, to remove the size effect of departments and make them comparable, it is more convenient to measure crimes per capita; the new variable results from dividing the total crime number by department by population number. The same calculation is made for the gross domestic product.

The logarithmic scale has many advantages. In addition to linearizing the link between two variables, this transformation enables the reduction of the dispersion of extreme observations. Moreover, the logarithmic coefficients estimated from a linear model are interpreted as elasticities.

Logarithmic transformation

# Compute new log scale variables

crimes$lcrimes_cap <- log(crimes$crimes/crimes$population)
crimes$lgdp_cap <- log(crimes$gdp_2011*1000000/crimes$population)
crimes$lpop <- log(crimes$population)

New estimation of crime determinants using transformed variables

# Estimating regression coefficients using "lm()" function.

MyModel_log <- lm(lcrimes_cap ~ lgdp_cap + poverty_index + unemp_rate + lpop, data=crimes)
# Showing results of the new estimation

summary(MyModel_log)

Comment on models comparison

From a qualitative perspective, the variables coefficients sign is the same in both estimations, except for the unemployment rate factor. The estimated coefficient of this variable is negative and nonsignificant in the first case and positive and significant in the transformed model, which reflects well what we would expect: uncertainty of employment may be another dimension of poverty. It then should contribute to enhancing crime rather than reducing it.

Even if the R-square of the first model is very high compared to the second one, using AIC and BIC criteria allows us to select the second estimates using rescaled variables as the most appropriate to explain the socio-economic determinants of crime in the French metropolitan departments. The logarithmic regression model produces very low AIC and BIC statistics than the prior model without transformation.

Instrumental Variables Estimator (IV)

Violation of errors independence assumption

In the present application to the case of crime determinants, we suspect the endogeneity of gross domestic product (gdp) as a measure of the department income (wealth) or as an approximation of the local standard of living. In fact, the omitted variables from the current specification, such as the economic local activities dynamics, the part of industrial activity, etc., could directly affect the department income which violates the independent-errors assumption. One of the major sources of endogeneity is the omitted variables problem. In this case, the endogenous bias occurs when an independent variable is correlated with the error term.

One way to correct this problem is to perform a two stage least-squares (2SLS) using the instrumental variables method (IV). This method proceeds as follows. In a first stage, a reduced form equation regresses the suspected endogenous variable, \(x\), on the instrument, \(z\), and the other independent variables of the system, \(X\). The second stage equation called the structural model, regresses the main endogenous variable, \(y\), on the predicted variable, \(\hat{x}\), derived from the first stage and the other independent variables except the instrument(s).

But the correct use of this method needs to find an instrument, \(z\), that should fulfils two conditions. The first one is that the candidate instrument, \(z\), must be correlated with the endogenous variable, \(x\), but uncorrelated with the error term, \(u\): \[ Cov(x, z) \neq 0 \; \; \text{and} \;\; Cov(x, u) = 0\]

The exclusion restrictions second condition implies that the instrument, \(z\), must not be correlated with the main endogenous variable, \(y\), and excluded from the structural equation.

# Install the "AER" package: Kleiber, Ch., Zeileis, A. (2008). Applied Econometrics with R, Springer-Verlag

# install.packages("AER")

Hausman test of endogeneity

As it is stated above before estimation there is no way to check the endogeneity assumption. The doubt of endogeneity of a given predictor is only based on theoretical considerations. After estimation Hausman test can be applied to check if the endogeneity assumption holds.

The Hausman (1978) test starts from the idea that if there is no difference between OLS and IV estimators, the predictor will be considered exogenous. Conversely, if there are systematic differences between the estimators, the suspected variable can be viewed as endogenous. The null hypothesis states: The suspected variable is exogenous.

Following Wooldridge (2013, p.535) the Hausman (1978) test can be applied as follows.

  1. Regress the suspected endogenous variable on the instruments and exogenous variables. Predict the residuals \(\hat{u}\).
  2. Add the predicted residuals to the structural equation (\(y\)) containing also the whole exogenous variables. Run a linear coefficient test for the estimated \(\hat{u}\) term from an OLS estimation.
  3. The decision rule states that the suspected predictor is endogenous if the term \(\hat{u}\) is significantly different from zero.
# Hausman procedure to test endogeneity assumption
# Regression 

HausmanTest <- lm(lgdp_cap ~ pupils +  unemp_rate + poverty_index + lpop, data = crimes)

# Predict residuals
gdp_residuals <- predict(HausmanTest)
# Testing the significance of residuals term via a regression within the 
# structural equation
endoTest <- lm(lcrimes_cap ~ lgdp_cap + unemp_rate + poverty_index + lpop +
                 gdp_residuals, data = crimes)

# Residuals term significance test

coeftest(endoTest, vcov = vcovHC)
## 
## t test of coefficients:
## 
##                 Estimate Std. Error  t value              Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   -13.235138   1.085718 -12.1902 < 0.00000000000000022 ***
## lgdp_cap        0.051205   0.028170   1.8177             0.0724785 .  
## unemp_rate      0.069951   0.013725   5.0968           0.000001926 ***
## poverty_index   0.029226   0.019183   1.5235             0.1311694    
## lpop            0.398248   0.038219  10.4202 < 0.00000000000000022 ***
## gdp_residuals   0.250063   0.067417   3.7092             0.0003613 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Comment on endogeneity test

The test of gdp_residuals term is highly significant, allowing to reject the null hypothesis of exogeneity and concluding that gdp_cap is endogenous. In other words, the 2SLS regression is preferred over the OLS estimates.

Important remark

The objective of presenting the IV two stages procedure is to show, from a methodological point of view, how we correct for endogeneity. However, doing so the standard errors of the second stage are not correct (Wooldridge, 2013, 5e eds, p.557). The ivreg function of the AER package fixes this issue and corrects automatically the standard errors.

# IV estimator using 'ivreg' function

ivreg_est <- ivreg(lcrimes_cap ~  lgdp_cap + unemp_rate + poverty_index + lpop | 
                                             unemp_rate + poverty_index + lpop +                                        pupils, data = crimes)
# Schow the estimates results of using the 'ivreg'  function.

summary(ivreg_est)

Panel data models

For panel data application, we use data from the Wooldridge package developed by Florian (2020) using data examples from the Wooldridge textbook on the Introductory Econometrics.

# Load the "Wooldridge" package
library(wooldridge)

# Load the 'plm' package on 'Panel data econometrics in R', by Yves Croissant 
# and Giovanni Millo.

library(plm)
## 
## Attachement du package : 'plm'
## Les objets suivants sont masqus depuis 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     between, lag, lead
wage <- data(wagepan)

Fixef effects estimation

Hausman specification test

# Hausman specification test, to choose between models
# H0: There is no difference between the two models

phtest(panel.fe, panel.re)
## 
##  Hausman Test
## 
## data:  lwage ~ educ + exper + expersq + union + south + married + black
## chisq = 42.004, df = 5, p-value = 0.00000005879
## alternative hypothesis: one model is inconsistent

To go in depth with R

There is a big community of researchers, scientists, and developers that produce and distribute packages, tutorials, and Rs courses. The majority of these materials are freely accessible on the Internet. In the reference chapter below, we give some of these materials, together with other academic publications. The most important, if not the unique advice, that we recommend is to try to learn R while practicing code (learning by doing), preferably by working on a real project of data analysis or econometric modeling.
